FACTORY METHOD PATTERN — CLEAN NOTES (INTERFACE VERSION)

---

1. PROBLEM

---

Direct object creation leads to tight coupling:

Example:
new EmailNotification()

Problems:

* Service depends on concrete classes
* Adding new type → modify existing code
* Violates Open/Closed Principle

---

2. CORE IDEA

---

Move object creation out of business logic.

Instead of:
Service → creates object

Do:
Service → asks Factory → gets object

---

3. KEY COMPONENTS

---

1. PRODUCT (Interface)

   * Defines WHAT to do
     Example:
     interface Notification {
     void send();
     }

2. CONCRETE PRODUCTS (Implementations)

   * Define HOW it works

     class EmailNotification implements Notification
     class SMSNotification implements Notification

3. FACTORY (Interface)

   * Defines HOW object will be created

     interface NotificationFactory {
     Notification createNotification();
     }

4. CONCRETE FACTORIES

   * Actually create objects

     class EmailFactory → returns EmailNotification
     class SMSFactory → returns SMSNotification

5. SERVICE (Business Logic)

   * Uses product but does NOT create it

6. CLIENT (Main)

   * Decides which factory to use

---

4. FLOW (IMPORTANT)

---

Main (Client)
↓
Choose Factory (EmailFactory)
↓
Pass Factory to Service
↓
Service calls:
factory.createNotification()
↓
Factory returns:
EmailNotification object
↓
Service calls:
notification.send()
↓
Output:
"Email sent"

---

5. MENTAL MODEL

---

Client → decides WHAT type
Factory → decides HOW to create
Product → does actual work
Service → uses product

---

6. BEFORE VS AFTER

---

WITHOUT FACTORY:

```
if(type == EMAIL) → new EmailNotification()
if(type == SMS) → new SMSNotification()
```

Problems:

* if-else everywhere
* hard to extend

WITH FACTORY:

```
Notification n = factory.createNotification();
n.send();
```

Benefits:

* No if-else
* Clean code
* Easy to extend

---

7. HOW TIGHT COUPLING IS REMOVED

---

Before:
Service → directly uses EmailNotification

After:
Service → uses Notification (interface)

Now:

* Service does NOT know about Email/SMS
* Only depends on abstraction

---

8. ADDING NEW TYPE (Push Notification)

---

Add only:

1. PushNotification implements Notification
2. PushFactory implements NotificationFactory

Change only in Main:

```
factory = new PushFactory();
```

NO CHANGE in:

* Service
* Existing factories
* Existing code

---

9. WHY USE FACTORY METHOD

---

* Removes tight coupling
* Follows Open/Closed Principle
* Cleaner architecture
* Easy to scale

---

10. TRADE-OFF

---

Cons:

* More classes
* Slightly complex initially

Pros:

* Maintainable
* Flexible
* Scalable

---

11. ONE-LINE SUMMARY

---

Factory Method = Move object creation out of business logic using interfaces.

---

12. FINAL MEMORY TRICK

---

Without Factory:
Service → new Object()

With Factory:
Service → Factory → Object

---

## END OF NOTES
